The word Preterism is from the Latin "prae" (before) and "ire" (to go), whose past participle is "praeteritus," meaning the subject has gone past. The word occurs in the future tense in the Latin Vulgate at Matt. 24:34 thus: "non praeteribit haec generatio donec omnia haec fiant" ("this generation shall not pass until all these things be fulfilled"). Preterism takes a contemporary-historical view of eschatology, holding that Revelation and related prophecies describe events contemporary to those to whom they were addressed. Specifically, Preterism views the latter days and second coming as being bound up in the world events marked by the persecution of Nero Caesar (AD 64-68), the Roman civil wars that erupted upon Nero's death ("the year of four emperors") (AD 68-70), and the destruction of Jerusalem by Rome (AD 67-70).

·∂ú·¥∏ Actus Apostolorum (Acts) 28:19 Contradicentibus autem Jud√¶is, coactus sum appellare C√¶sarem, non quasi gentem meam habens aliquid accusare And through the contradicting Jews, I was forced to appeal to the C√¶sar, not as if having something to accuse my people of. This is an interesting example of the power of the Latin ablative case, which despite most strongly resembling the modern Romance nouns, actually had a very unique use as stating the means or where/when (either time or space) that something occurred. Here, in the context of St. Paul's trial, he describes how through the means or because of the Jews (judaei - nominative plural, judaeis - ablative plural) which were contradicting his pleas of innocence, here a Latin present participle (no longer existing in Romace languages, replaced with the gerund) is used as a declined adjective - he is forced (passive construct) to appeal to (the) C√¶sar. The ablative case is one of the biggest differences between Classical and Late/Medieval Latin as in Classical Latin you could just have a noun declined in the ablative case to indicate the entire idea of it being the means or time/place of something. But in Late Latin and thus the Romance langauges, a proposition such as pro or per became required (which in most Romance languages merged into por). This is mainly due to phonological reasons, as by this point, the ablative case was pronounced the same as the accusative form. Compare jud√¶o (jew, ablative singular) - pronounced /ju.de.u/ in Vulgar Latin (but ju.dai.o in Classical Latin) with jud√¶um (jew, accusative singular) - pronounced /ju.de.u/ in Vulgar Latin (but ju.dai. äÃÉ/ in Classical Latin). ·∂ú·¥∏ Rhaeto-Romance: Ladin: Romanian retained the vulgar name for Latin; 'Roman language', but did any Romance language retain the actual name of Latin? In fact, yes: one. Historically there were more, such as: Latino - the main designation of the Mozarabic language (search Mozarabic for more information), and Ladino - the archaic Jewish dialect of Spanish which is now virtually extinct. But one remains, Ladin, a highly Germanified Rhaeto-Romance language spoken in Alto Adige/S√ºdtirol in Northern Italy (a former Austrian territory). This group of Romance languages include two other surviving tongues - Furlan (due to the fact it's spoken in Fruili, Italy), and Romansh, which is also impressive for preserving the name of Romanice or Romance for the language, which is spoken in South Eastern Switzerland (which is majority German speaking). These Rhaeto-Romance languages are in some aspects very innovative - with many Germanic borrowings and the typical French trait of losing final vowels (compare Ladin nost with Latin nostrum and French notre (our)), but also very archaic. They retain the initial palatalization of ci/ce like Italian, compare Ladin ciel /Ààt‚Äå É…õl/ (heaven) with Italian cielo /Ààt‚Äå É…õlo/, and Spanish cielo /sj…õlo/ where it has further palatized into an S sound. And the most unique trait of all, the retention in some cases of Vulgar latin initial /w/. Compare Romansh uiara /wjara/ (war) with Ladin viera /vjera/ and with Vulgar Latin uerra /w…õr.ra/ vs. all other Romance languages where uerra evolved into guerra and later guerre in modern French.
